                    <property name="label" translatable="yes">After a year of C++, I decided it would be a "good" idea to completely remake my largest programming project from scratch.

In the Fall of 2006, I started the epic task of remaking the game "Kye", originally written by Colin Garbutt for Windows 3.1. Garbutt made the game shareware to benefit the Save The Children foundation. Since the game hasn't a glimpse of hope of running on today's non-16-bit computers, I decided to rewrite the game from scratch, using graphics made by a few of my friends.

Eight months later, I couldn't stand it anymore. I had to completely rewrite various parts of the game due to innate flaws in my design. The game was practically finished, even though the source code was the ugliest thing I saw. I wanted to make a level editor, but I never brought myself to spend another great length of time slaving over Dev-C++ and the Win32 API.

Now, with Ubuntu Linux and a ton of nifty tools at my disposal, I decided to go for it a second time! After one year and nine days since I first attempted a massively complex game, here goes nothing.

So, here it is. I made this thing in Python, with a healthy dash of pyGtk. Even though I spent a year and four months slaving off-and-on over my text editor, I'd say the entire experience has been enjoyable, productive and educational.

If you need anything, I'll be on IRC at irc.freenode.net, in the channel ##c++-social, with the nickname Kaedenn.

Enjoy!</property>
